# Pydantic Model Hygiene

## Exclude non-serializable fields

Any field that holds a raw platform object, socket, connection, or other non-serializable value must use `Field(exclude=True)` so Pydantic never tries to serialize or validate it.

```python
# BAD — Pydantic will attempt to serialize the raw object
raw: Any = None

# GOOD — excluded from serialization, still accessible in code
raw: Any = Field(default=None, exclude=True)
```

## Use explicit `Field(...)` for semantic defaults

When a default has special meaning (e.g. empty list, zero cooldown, exclusion), prefer `Field(default=..., ...)` over bare assignment so the intent is visible and documented.

```python
# Acceptable for simple scalars
text: str

# Prefer Field for complex defaults or when extra metadata applies
citations: list[SourceChunk] = Field(default_factory=list)
ephemeral: bool = Field(default=False, description="Only the invoking user sees this")
```

## Model inheritance

All cross-platform data models (events, responses) inherit from `pydantic.BaseModel`. Do not use plain dataclasses for models that cross module boundaries or may be serialized. Use `dataclass(frozen=True, slots=True)` only for internal value objects that never need serialization (e.g. `CommandSpec`).
